\begin_layout Standard
Using Bayes rule and the independence assumption of the na
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
"{i}
\end_layout

\end_inset

ve Bayes model, we can formulate the agent's belief about the emotion vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 after observing features 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}...f_{t}$
\end_inset

 as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}P(\varepsilon|f_{1},...,f_{t})= & \frac{\prod_{i=1}^{t}\left[P(f_{i}|\varepsilon)\right]P(\varepsilon)}{\prod_{i=1}^{t}P(f_{i})}\end{split}
.\label{eq:naivebayes}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 When the game begins the agent can start with a uniform prior on its belief
 of which emotion is likely or it can use information obtained in previously
 played games.
 In the experiment of this paper, we use a uniform prior, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\varepsilon=e_{k})=1/|E|,\thickspace\forall k=1...|E|$
\end_inset

.
 We chose to use the uniform prior to start with because our training data
 contains many single count training instances and because we want to examine
 how the system performs with less constraints.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:naivebayes"

\end_inset

, the posterior belief of the agent of emotion 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{k}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\varepsilon=e_{k}|f_{1},...,f_{t})$
\end_inset

 is computed only after the agent has asked the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 questions.
 In contrast the formulation we use is dynamic in that the agent updates
 its belief at each time point based on the posterior probability of the
 previous step, i.e., at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P(\varepsilon|f_{1},...,f_{t}) & = & \frac{P(f_{t}|\varepsilon)P(\varepsilon|f_{1},...,f_{t-1})}{P(f_{t})}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We introduce a new variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{t,k}=P(\varepsilon=e_{k}|f_{1},...,f_{t})$
\end_inset

 for the agent's belief about emotion 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and postulate that the agent's current prior belief is the posterior belief
 of the previous step.
 Then, the agent's belief unfolds according to the formula:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\beta_{0,k} & = & P(\varepsilon=e_{k})=1/|E|\nonumber \\
\beta_{1,k} & = & \frac{P(f_{1}|\varepsilon=e_{k})}{P(f_{1})}\beta_{0,k}\nonumber \\
\beta_{t,k} & = & \frac{P(f_{t}|\varepsilon=e_{k})}{P(f_{t})}\beta_{t-1,k}\label{eq:adaptive}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Decomposing the computation of the posterior belief allows the agent to
 choose the best question to ask the user at each turn, rather than having
 a fixed battery of questions.
 In this case, we define 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

best
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as the question that is most likely to have a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

yes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 answer given 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 This criterion indicates how often the question was observed in the training
 data in the context of emotions as they are currently weighted by 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\varepsilon|f_{1},...,f_{t-1})$
\end_inset

.
 The agent asks the best question and takes the user's response as input.
 It then parses the input to classify it into one of {
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

yes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

other
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

}.
 This information is then used to update the agent's belief as to which
 emotion in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 in most likely.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Identity questions are a special type of question where the agent makes
