\begin_layout Section
A Computational Model of Curiosity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous result, in which the subjects rated the agent as being relatively
 human-like even in cases when the EMO20Q task performance was low, seems
 to indicate that there is something human-like in the search for knowledge,
 rather than having a complete representation of emotions that would allow
 it to guess correctly and win at EMO20Q more often.
 In an earlier paper 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kazemzadeh2011b"

\end_inset

, we proposed a model for verbally exploring a sparse graphical representation
 of an agent's knowledge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Representing the agent's knowledge as an adjacency graph 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, allows us to use methods from collaborative filtering, social network
 analysis, and spectral graph theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kunegis2009,Hou2005"

\end_inset

.
 In this paper, we use the number of zero eigenvalues of the Laplacian of
 the graph 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to determine the number of connected components of the graph.
 This can be seen as a measure of the sparsity of our data and can be used
 to identify the questions that must be asked of certain emotions in order
 to connect the graph components.
 In this way, we can have a rudimentary representation of curiosity in terms
 of the agent's exploration of this graph.
 To construct this graph we built a graph in the following way: questions
 and answers are nodes in the graph which are linked by edges labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 if the question is answered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

yes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of that emotion and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 if the question is answered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the emotion.
 Thus the graph 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is bipartite in that emotion nodes are connected to question nodes, but
 there are no edges between any two emotion nodes or between any two question
 nodes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used the Laplacian 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 of this graph to calculate the connectivity and to identify which nodes
 were unconnected.
 The Laplacian 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 of a signed graph is calculated by subtracting the absolute adjacency matrix
 
\begin_inset Formula $|A|$
\end_inset

 from the diagonal absolute degree matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{D}_{ii}=\sum_{j}|A_{ij}|$
\end_inset

 :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\bar{D}-|A|
\]

\end_inset

From the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 we can tell the number of connected components of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by counting the number of zero eigenvalues.
 Thus, if there are three eigenvalues that equal zero, the graph is composed
 of three separate connected components.
 A graph Laplacian with one zero eigenvalue is a single connected graph.
 Moreover, the lowest 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 non-zero eigenvalues can be used to project nodes in the graph into an
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional space (this is similar to principal components analysis (PCA)
 except that in PCA instances are projected to be farther apart, whereas
 in the graph projection, connected nodes ought to be projected close by).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If an agent has identified that it has unconnected knowledge, how can it
 then plan questions to address the knowledge goal of connecting the components
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

? To answer this, we must define the notion of a 
\emph on
walk
\emph default
 on a graph.
 A walk of length 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 on graph 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that joins vertices 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a sequence of vertices 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}\ldots u_{l}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}=u_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}=u_{l}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}$
\end_inset

 are adjacent for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\le t\le l$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Lemma 2.5"
key "Biggs1974"

\end_inset

, the number of walks of length 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that join 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the entry in cell 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)$
\end_inset

 of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{l}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, by taking repeated powers of the absolute adjacency matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $|A|$
\end_inset

, we can determine if nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

 are connected by walks of length 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 Since the graph is bipartite, the walks from question nodes to other question
 nodes or from object nodes to other object nodes will always be even length,
 and conversely, walks between question and object nodes will be odd length.
 This behavior is undesirable because we wish to preserve connectedness
 properties across repeated powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{l}.$
\end_inset

 To remedy this undesirable behavior we can augment the adjacency matrix
 
\begin_inset Formula $|A|$
\end_inset

 by adding the identity matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 to it.
 At this point, we can say that vertices 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

 are connected by a walk of length 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
or less
\emph default
 if the entry 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(A+I)^{l}$
\end_inset

 is non-zero.
 The proof of this, by contradiction, is that if we imagine that vertices
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

 are connected by some walk of length 
\begin_inset Formula $k<l$
\end_inset

, but not of length 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

, then there must not be self-loop from 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

 to itself after the walk of length 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 However, since we added the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 matrix to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 we know that there are in fact self-loops on all of the vertices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preceding fact allows us to state an alternative test for connectedness
 and also allows us to identify the question-object pairs that need to be
 asked to complete the agent's knowledge.
 This test can be stated as follows: the graph 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is connected if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(|A|+I)^{M+N-1}
\]

\end_inset

 has no zero entries, where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the number of emotions and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the number of questions.
 This is because the length of a walk with distinct steps, a 
\emph on
path
\emph default
, is at most one less than the number of vertices in the graph, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $M+N-1$
\end_inset

, which would be the case if the graph were a linked list.
 The question-object pairs that correspond to zero entries in this matrix
 are precisely the set of candidate questions that need to be asked to connect
 the agent's knowledge and choosing which one to ask can be determined by
 using 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 to project the current state of the dialog into the graph's space.
\end_layout

