\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main goals of this paper were to use question-asking to observe natural
 language descriptions of emotion in a natural context and to computationally
 model the social processes that support the referential link between language
 and emotions.
 We presented the emotion twenty questions (EMO20Q) game and showed that
 the level of human performance was high despite not limiting the players
 to any specific emotion vocabulary.
 We also presented two computational models for automated players of EMO20Q.
 First, we showed that a sequential Bayesian belief update algorithm could
 model the question asking player's belief state over time.
 Second, we showed a graphical model can represent the connectivity of an
 agent's knowledge which can be used to choose questions that represent
 unknown states as a way to model curiosity.
 This framework was inspired by a method of question-asking that was proposed
 by the ancient philosopher Socrates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We deem that future advances in affective computing can come from studying
 emotions at a finer grain, as they are described in natural language.
 We plan to continue studying this phenomena in several ways.
 First, we hope to see the effect of modality on how people describe emotions
 in natural language.
 The current work was limited to text-based chat, so paralinguistic information
 that may help to convey emotional data was minimized.
 Including audio and video data may allow greater convergence of the players
 to agree upon the unknown emotion.
 Another area of future research will be to examine the answerer role.
 The current research focused on the questioner role, but the answerer role
 will offer additional challenges and insights.
 In particular, automating the answerer role will require more robust natural
 language understanding and it will allow a closed loop simulation where
 both roles of EMO20Q are played by computer.
 
\end_layout

